# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: boost-converter
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:boost-converter/boost-converter] A **boost converter** or **step-up converter** is a DC-to-DC converter that increases voltage, while decreasing current, from its input (*supply*) to its output (*load*).
[src:boost-converter/boost-converter] It is a class of switched-mode power supply (SMPS) containing at least two semiconductors, a diode and a transistor, and at least one energy storage element: a capacitor, inductor, or the two in combination.
[src:boost-converter/boost-converter] To reduce voltage ripple, filters made of capacitors (sometimes in combination with inductors) are normally added to such a converter's output (load-side filter) and input (supply-side filter).
[src:boost-converter/boost-converter] Power for the boost converter can come from any suitable DC source, such as batteries, solar panels, rectifiers, and DC generators.
[src:boost-converter/boost-converter] A process that changes one DC voltage to a different DC voltage is called DC-to-DC conversion.
[src:boost-converter/boost-converter] A boost converter is a DC-to-DC converter with an output voltage greater than the source voltage.
[src:boost-converter/boost-converter] A boost converter is sometimes called a step-up converter since it "steps up" the source voltage.
[src:boost-converter/boost-converter] Since power ( ${\textstyle P=U\cdot I}$ ) must be conserved, the output current is lower than the source current.
[src:boost-converter/boost-converter] The hydraulic ram can be seen as the hydraulic analogue to a boost converter.
[src:boost-converter/boost-converter] For high efficiency, the switched-mode power supply (SMPS) switch must turn on and off quickly and have low losses.
[src:boost-converter/boost-converter] The advent of a commercial semiconductor switch in the 1950s represented a major milestone that made SMPSs such as the boost converter possible.
[src:boost-converter/boost-converter] The major DC-to-DC converters were developed in the early 1960s when semiconductor switches had become available.
[src:boost-converter/boost-converter] The aerospace industry’s need for small, lightweight, and efficient power converters led to the converter’s rapid development.
[src:boost-converter/boost-converter] Switched systems such as SMPS are a challenge to design since their models depend on whether a switch is opened or closed.
[src:boost-converter/boost-converter] Middlebrook from Caltech in 1977 published the models for DC-to-DC converters used today.
[src:boost-converter/boost-converter] Middlebrook averaged the circuit configurations for each switch state in a technique called state-space averaging.
[src:boost-converter/boost-converter] This simplification reduced two systems into one.
[src:boost-converter/boost-converter] The new model led to insightful design equations which helped the growth of SMPS.
[src:boost-converter/boost-converter] Battery power systems often stack cells in series to achieve higher voltage.
[src:boost-converter/boost-converter] However, sufficient stacking of cells is not possible in many high voltage applications due to lack of space.
[src:boost-converter/boost-converter] Boost converters can increase the voltage and reduce the number of cells.
[src:boost-converter/boost-converter] Two battery-powered applications that use boost converters are used in hybrid electric vehicles (HEV) and lighting systems.
[src:boost-converter/boost-converter] The NHW20 model Toyota Prius HEV uses a 500 V motor.
[src:boost-converter/boost-converter] Without a boost converter, the Prius would need nearly 417 cells to power the motor.
[src:boost-converter/boost-converter] However, a Prius actually uses only 168 cells and boosts the battery voltage from 202 V to 500 V.
[src:boost-converter/boost-converter] Boost converters also power devices at smaller scale applications, such as portable lighting systems.
[src:boost-converter/boost-converter] A white LED typically requires 3.3 V to emit light, and a boost converter can step up the voltage from a single 1.5 V alkaline cell to power the lamp.
[src:boost-converter/boost-converter] An unregulated boost converter is used as the voltage increase mechanism in the circuit known as the "Joule thief", based on blocking oscillator concepts.
[src:boost-converter/boost-converter] This circuit topology is used with low power battery applications, and is aimed at the ability of a boost converter to "steal" the remaining energy in a battery.
[src:boost-converter/boost-converter] This energy would otherwise be wasted since the low voltage of a nearly depleted battery makes it unusable for a normal load.
[src:boost-converter/boost-converter] This voltage decrease occurs as batteries become depleted, and is a characteristic of the ubiquitous alkaline battery.
[src:boost-converter/boost-converter] Since the equation for power is ⁠ $\textstyle P={\frac {V^{2}}{R}}$ ⁠, and ⁠ R ⁠ tends to be stable, power available to the load goes down significantly as voltage decreases.
[src:boost-converter/boost-converter] The special kind of boost-converters called voltage-lift type boost converters are used in solar photovoltaic (PV) systems.
[src:boost-converter/boost-converter] These power converters add up the passive components (diode, inductor and capacitor) of a traditional boost-converter to improve the power quality and increase the performance of complete PV system.
[src:boost-converter/boost-converter] The key principle that drives the boost converter is the tendency of an inductor to resist changes in current by either increasing or decreasing the energy stored in the inductor's magnetic field.
[src:boost-converter/boost-converter] In a boost converter, the output voltage is always higher than the input voltage.
[src:boost-converter/boost-converter] A schematic of a boost power stage is shown in Figure 1.
[src:boost-converter/boost-converter] When the switch is closed ('on-state'), current flows through the inductor in the clockwise direction and the inductor stores some energy by generating a magnetic field.
[src:boost-converter/boost-converter] The polarity of the left side of the inductor is positive.
[src:boost-converter/boost-converter] When the switch is opened ('off-state'), the magnetic field previously created will be reduced in energy to maintain the current through the inductor.
[src:boost-converter/boost-converter] The polarity of the inductor will be reversed, which means the left side of the inductor will become negative.
[src:boost-converter/boost-converter] If the switch is cycled fast enough, the inductor will not discharge fully in between charging stages, and the load will always see a voltage greater than that of the input source alone when the switch is opened.
[src:boost-converter/boost-converter] Also, while the switch is opened, the capacitor, in parallel with the load, is charged to this combined voltage.
[src:boost-converter/boost-converter] When the switch is then closed, and the right-hand side is shorted out from the left-hand side, the capacitor is, therefore, able to provide the voltage and energy to the load.
[src:boost-converter/boost-converter] During this time, the blocking diode prevents the capacitor from discharging through the switch.
[src:boost-converter/boost-converter] The switch must, of course, be opened again fast enough to prevent the capacitor from discharging too much.
[src:boost-converter/boost-converter] This results in transferring the energy accumulated during the on-state into the capacitor.
[src:boost-converter/boost-converter] The input current is the same as the inductor current, as shown in Figure 2.
[src:boost-converter/boost-converter] So, it is not discontinuous as in the buck converter, and the requirements on the input filter are relaxed compared to a buck converter.
[src:boost-converter/boost-converter] When a boost converter operates in continuous mode, the current through the inductor, ⁠ $I_{\mathrm {L} }$ ⁠, never falls to zero.
[src:boost-converter/boost-converter] Figure 3 shows the typical waveforms of inductor current and voltage in a converter operating in this mode.
[src:boost-converter/boost-converter] In the steady state, the DC (average) voltage across the inductor must be zero so that after each cycle, the inductor returns the same state because the voltage across the inductor is proportional to the rate of change of current through it (explained in more detail below).
[src:boost-converter/boost-converter] Note in Figure 1 that the left-hand side of ⁠ L ⁠ is at ⁠ $V_{\mathrm {i} }$ ⁠, and the right-hand side of ⁠ L ⁠ sees the $V_{\mathrm {S} }$ voltage waveform from Figure 3.
[src:boost-converter/boost-converter] The average value of $V_{\mathrm {S} }$ is ⁠ $(1-D)V_{\mathrm {o} }$ ⁠, where ⁠ D ⁠ is the duty cycle of the waveform driving the switch.
[src:boost-converter/boost-converter] It represents the fraction of the commutation period T during which the switch is on.
[src:boost-converter/boost-converter] Therefore, D ranges between 0 (S is never on) and 1 (S is always on).
[src:boost-converter/boost-converter] During the off-state, the switch S is open, so the inductor current flows through the load.
[src:boost-converter/boost-converter] As we consider that the converter operates in steady state conditions, the amount of energy stored in each of its components has to be the same at the beginning and at the end of a commutation cycle.
[src:boost-converter/boost-converter] So, the inductor current has to be the same at the start and end of the commutation cycle.
[src:boost-converter/boost-converter] The above equation shows that the output voltage is always higher than the input voltage (as the duty cycle goes from 0 to 1), and that it increases with ⁠ D ⁠, theoretically to infinity as D approaches 1.
[src:boost-converter/boost-converter] This is why this converter is sometimes referred to as a 'step-up' converter.
[src:boost-converter/boost-converter] If the ripple amplitude of the current is too high, the inductor may be completely discharged before the end of a whole commutation cycle.
[src:boost-converter/boost-converter] In this case, the current through the inductor falls to zero during part of the period (see waveforms in Figure 4).
[src:boost-converter/boost-converter] Although the difference is slight, it has a strong effect on the output voltage equation.
[src:boost-converter/boost-converter] The load current $I_{\mathrm {o} }$ is equal to the average diode current ⁠ $I_{\mathrm {D} }$ ⁠.
[src:boost-converter/boost-converter] As can be seen in Figure 4, the diode current is equal to the inductor current during the off-state.
[src:boost-converter/boost-converter] The average value of $I_{\mathrm {o} }$ can be sorted out geometrically from Figure 4.
[src:boost-converter/boost-converter] Compared to the expression of the output voltage gain for continuous mode, this expression is much more complicated.
[src:boost-converter/boost-converter] Furthermore, in discontinuous operation, the output voltage gain not only depends on the duty cycle ⁠ D ⁠, but also on the inductor value ⁠ L ⁠, the input voltage ⁠ $V_{\mathrm {i} }$ ⁠, the commutation period ⁠ T ⁠, and the output current ⁠ $I_{\mathrm {o} }$ ⁠.
[src:boost-converter/buck-boost-converter] The **buck–boost converter** is a type of DC-to-DC converter that has an output voltage magnitude that is either greater than or less than the input voltage magnitude.
[src:boost-converter/buck-boost-converter] It is equivalent to a flyback converter using a single inductor instead of a transformer.
[src:boost-converter/buck-boost-converter] Two different topologies are called *buck–boost converter*.
[src:boost-converter/buck-boost-converter] Both of them can produce a range of output voltages, ranging from much larger (in absolute magnitude) than the input voltage, down to almost zero.
[src:boost-converter/buck-boost-converter] In the inverting topology, the output voltage is of the opposite polarity than the input.
[src:boost-converter/buck-boost-converter] This is a switched-mode power supply with a similar circuit configuration to the boost converter and the buck converter.
[src:boost-converter/buck-boost-converter] The output voltage is adjustable based on the duty cycle of the switching transistor.
[src:boost-converter/buck-boost-converter] One possible drawback of this converter is that the switch does not have a terminal at ground; this complicates the driving circuitry.
[src:boost-converter/buck-boost-converter] However, this drawback is of no consequence if the power supply is isolated from the load circuit (if, for example, the supply is a battery) because the supply and diode polarity can simply be reversed.
[src:boost-converter/buck-boost-converter] When they can be reversed, the switch can be placed either on the ground side or the supply side.
[src:boost-converter/buck-boost-converter] When a buck (step-down) converter is combined with a boost (step-up) converter, the output voltage is typically of the same polarity of the input, and can be lower or higher than the input.
[src:boost-converter/buck-boost-converter] Like the buck and boost converters, the operation of the buck–boost is best understood in terms of the inductor's "reluctance" to allow rapid change in current.
[src:boost-converter/buck-boost-converter] From the initial state in which nothing is charged and the switch is open, the current through the inductor is zero.
[src:boost-converter/buck-boost-converter] When the switch is first closed, the blocking diode prevents current from flowing into the right hand side of the circuit, so it must all flow through the inductor.
[src:boost-converter/buck-boost-converter] However, since the inductor doesn't allow rapid current change, it will initially keep the current low by opposing the voltage provided by the source.
[src:boost-converter/buck-boost-converter] Over time, the inductor will allow the current to slowly increase.
[src:boost-converter/buck-boost-converter] In an ideal circuit the voltage across the inductor would remain constant, but when the inherent resistance of wiring, switch and the inductor itself is taken into account, the effective (electro-motive) voltage across the inductor will decrease as the current increases.
[src:boost-converter/buck-boost-converter] Also during this time, the inductor will store energy in the form of a magnetic field.
[src:boost-converter/buck-boost-converter] If the current through the inductor L never falls to zero during a commutation cycle, the converter is said to operate in continuous mode.
[src:boost-converter/buck-boost-converter] The current and voltage waveforms in an ideal converter can be seen in Figure 3.
[src:boost-converter/buck-boost-converter] From *t* = 0 to *t* = *DT*, the converter is in on-state, so the switch S is closed.
[src:boost-converter/buck-boost-converter] Therefore D ranges between 0 (S is never on) and 1 (S is always on).
[src:boost-converter/buck-boost-converter] As we consider that the converter operates in steady-state conditions, the amount of energy stored in each of its components has to be the same at the beginning and at the end of a commutation cycle.
[src:boost-converter/buck-boost-converter] From the above expression it can be seen that the polarity of the output voltage is always negative (because the duty cycle goes from 0 to 1), and that its absolute value increases with D, theoretically up to minus infinity when D approaches 1.
[src:boost-converter/buck-boost-converter] Apart from the polarity, this converter is either step-up (a boost converter) or step-down (a buck converter).
[src:boost-converter/buck-boost-converter] Thus it is named a buck–boost converter.
[src:boost-converter/buck-boost-converter] In some cases, the amount of energy required by the load is small enough to be transferred in a time smaller than the whole commutation period.
[src:boost-converter/buck-boost-converter] In this case, the current through the inductor falls to zero during part of the period.
[src:boost-converter/buck-boost-converter] The only difference in the principle described above is that the inductor is completely discharged at the end of the commutation cycle (see waveforms in figure 4).
[src:boost-converter/buck-boost-converter] Although slight, the difference has a strong effect on the output voltage equation.
[src:boost-converter/buck-boost-converter] The load current *I*o is equal to the average diode current *I*D.
[src:boost-converter/buck-boost-converter] As can be seen on figure 4, the diode current is equal to the inductor current during the off-state.
[src:boost-converter/buck-boost-converter] Compared to the expression of the output voltage gain for the continuous mode, this expression is much more complicated.
[src:boost-converter/buck-boost-converter] Furthermore, in discontinuous operation, the output voltage not only depends on the duty cycle, but also on the inductor value, the input voltage and the output current.
[src:boost-converter/buck-boost-converter] As told at the beginning of this section, the converter operates in discontinuous mode when low current is drawn by the load, and in continuous mode at higher load current levels.
[src:boost-converter/buck-boost-converter] As *I*o,lim is the current at the limit between continuous and discontinuous modes of operations, it satisfies the expressions of both modes.
[src:boost-converter/buck-boost-converter] These expressions have been plotted in figure 5.
[src:boost-converter/buck-boost-converter] The difference in behavior between the continuous and discontinuous modes can be seen clearly.
[src:boost-converter/buck-boost-converter] The four-switch converter combines the buck and boost converters.
[src:boost-converter/buck-boost-converter] It can operate in either the buck or the boost mode.
[src:boost-converter/buck-boost-converter] In either mode, only one switch controls the duty cycle, another is for commutation and must be operated inversely to the former one, and the remaining two switches are in a fixed position.
[src:boost-converter/buck-boost-converter] A two-switch buck–boost converter can be built with two diodes, but upgrading the diodes to FET switches doesn't cost much extra while efficiency improves due to the lower voltage drop.
[src:boost-converter/buck-boost-converter] In the analysis above, no dissipative elements (resistors) have been considered.
[src:boost-converter/buck-boost-converter] That means that the power is transmitted without losses from the input voltage source to the load.
[src:boost-converter/buck-boost-converter] However, parasitic resistances exist in all circuits, due to the resistivity of the materials they are made from.
[src:boost-converter/buck-boost-converter] Therefore, a fraction of the power managed by the converter is dissipated by these parasitic resistances.
[src:boost-converter/buck-boost-converter] For the sake of simplicity, we consider here that the inductor is the only non-ideal component, and that it is equivalent to an inductor and a resistor in series.
[src:boost-converter/buck-boost-converter] This assumption is acceptable because an inductor is made of one long wound piece of wire, so it is likely to exhibit a non-negligible parasitic resistance *R*L.
[src:boost-converter/buck-boost-converter] Furthermore, current flows through the inductor both in the on and the off states.
[src:boost-converter/buck-boost-converter] where ${\bar {V_{\mathrm {L} }}}$ and ${\bar {V_{\mathrm {S} }}}$ are respectively the average voltage across the inductor and the switch over the commutation cycle.
[src:boost-converter/buck-boost-converter] If we consider that the converter operates in steady-state, the average current through the inductor is constant.
[src:boost-converter/buck-boost-converter] When the switch is in the on-state, *V*S = 0.
[src:boost-converter/buck-boost-converter] The output current is the opposite of the inductor current during the off-state.
[src:boost-converter/buck-boost-converter] The average inductor current is therefore: ${\bar {I_{\mathrm {L} }}}={\frac {-I_{\mathrm {o} }}{1-D}}.$ Assuming the output current and voltage have negligible ripple, the load of the converter can be considered purely resistive.
[src:boost-converter/buck-boost-converter] If the inductor resistance is zero, the equation above becomes equal to that of the *ideal* case.
[src:boost-converter/buck-boost-converter] But when *R*L increases, the voltage gain of the converter decreases compared to the ideal case.
[src:boost-converter/buck-boost-converter] Furthermore, the influence of *R*L increases with the duty cycle.
[src:boost-converter/dc-to-dc-converter] A **DC-to-DC converter** is an electronic circuit or electromechanical device that converts a source of direct current (DC) from one voltage level to another DC.
[src:boost-converter/dc-to-dc-converter] It is a type of electric power converter.
[src:boost-converter/dc-to-dc-converter] Power levels range from very low (small batteries) to very high (high-voltage power transmission).
[src:boost-converter/dc-to-dc-converter] Before the development of power semiconductors, one way to convert the voltage of a DC supply to a higher voltage, for low-power applications, was to convert it to AC by using a vibrator, then by a step-up transformer, and finally a rectifier.
[src:boost-converter/dc-to-dc-converter] Where higher power was needed, a motor–generator unit was often used, in which an electric motor drove a generator that produced the desired voltage.
[src:boost-converter/dc-to-dc-converter] The introduction of power semiconductors and integrated circuits made it economically viable by use of techniques described below.
[src:boost-converter/dc-to-dc-converter] For example, first is converting the DC power supply to high-frequency AC as an input of a transformer - it is small, light, and cheap due to the high frequency — that changes the voltage which gets rectified back to DC.
[src:boost-converter/dc-to-dc-converter] Although by 1976 transistor car radio receivers did not require high voltages, some amateur radio operators continued to use vibrator supplies and dynamotors for mobile transceivers requiring high voltages even though transistorized power supplies were available.
[src:boost-converter/dc-to-dc-converter] While it was possible to derive a *lower* voltage from a higher with a linear regulator or even a resistor, these methods dissipated the excess energy as heat; energy-efficient conversion became possible only with solid-state switch-mode circuits.
[src:boost-converter/dc-to-dc-converter] DC-to-DC converters are used in portable electronic devices such as cellular phones and laptop computers, which are supplied with power from batteries primarily.
[src:boost-converter/dc-to-dc-converter] Such electronic devices often contain several sub-circuits, each with its own voltage level requirement different from that supplied by the battery or an external supply (sometimes higher or lower than the supply voltage).
[src:boost-converter/dc-to-dc-converter] Additionally, the battery voltage declines as its stored energy is drained.
[src:boost-converter/dc-to-dc-converter] Switched DC to DC converters offer a method to increase voltage from a partially lowered battery voltage thereby saving space instead of using multiple batteries to accomplish the same thing.
[src:boost-converter/dc-to-dc-converter] Most DC-to-DC converter circuits also regulate the output voltage.
[src:boost-converter/dc-to-dc-converter] Some exceptions include high-efficiency LED power sources, which are a kind of DC to DC converter that regulates the current through the LEDs, and simple charge pumps which double or triple the output voltage.
[src:boost-converter/dc-to-dc-converter] DC-to-DC converters which are designed to maximize the energy harvest for photovoltaic systems and for wind turbines are called power optimizers.
[src:boost-converter/dc-to-dc-converter] In electric vehicles, DC-DC converters step down the high voltage of the propulsion battery to 12 volts to allow use of accessories such as lighting, climate control fans, entertainment electronics, and other systems.
[src:boost-converter/dc-to-dc-converter] This converter may also recharge the 12 volt auxiliary battery used for startup and standby loads such as keyless entry or security systems while the vehicle is idle.
[src:boost-converter/dc-to-dc-converter] Most DC-to-DC converters are designed to move power in only one direction, from dedicated input to output.
[src:boost-converter/dc-to-dc-converter] However, all switching regulator topologies can be made bidirectional and able to move power in either direction by replacing all diodes with independently controlled active rectification.
[src:boost-converter/dc-to-dc-converter] A bidirectional converter is useful, for example, in applications requiring regenerative braking of vehicles, where power is supplied *to* the wheels while driving, but supplied *by* the wheels when braking.
[src:boost-converter/dc-to-dc-converter] Although they require few components, switching converters are electronically complex.
[src:boost-converter/dc-to-dc-converter] Like all high-frequency circuits, their components must be carefully specified and physically arranged to achieve stable operation and to keep switching noise (EMI / RFI) at acceptable levels.
[src:boost-converter/dc-to-dc-converter] Their cost is higher than linear regulators in voltage-dropping applications, but their cost has been decreasing with advances in chip design.
[src:boost-converter/dc-to-dc-converter] DC-to-DC converters are available as integrated circuits (ICs) requiring few additional components.
[src:boost-converter/dc-to-dc-converter] Converters are also available as complete hybrid circuit modules, ready for use within an electronic assembly.
[src:boost-converter/dc-to-dc-converter] Linear regulators which are used to output a stable DC independent of input voltage and output load from a higher but less stable input by dissipating excess volt-amperes as heat, could be described literally as DC-to-DC converters, but this is not usual usage.
[src:boost-converter/dc-to-dc-converter] There are also simple capacitive voltage doubler and Dickson multiplier circuits using diodes and capacitors to multiply a DC voltage by an integer value, typically delivering only a small current.
[src:boost-converter/dc-to-dc-converter] In these DC-to-DC converters, energy is periodically stored within and released from a magnetic field in an inductor or a transformer, typically within a frequency range of 300 kHz to 10 MHz.
[src:boost-converter/dc-to-dc-converter] By adjusting the duty cycle of the charging voltage (that is, the ratio of the on/off times), the amount of power transferred to a load can be more easily controlled, though this control can also be applied to the input current, the output current, or to maintain constant power.
[src:boost-converter/dc-to-dc-converter] Transformer-based converters may provide isolation between input and output.
[src:boost-converter/dc-to-dc-converter] In general, the term *DC-to-DC converter* refers to one of these switching converters.
[src:boost-converter/dc-to-dc-converter] These circuits are the heart of a switched-mode power supply.
[src:boost-converter/dc-to-dc-converter] A converter may be designed to operate in continuous mode at high power, and in discontinuous mode at low power.
[src:boost-converter/dc-to-dc-converter] The half bridge and flyback topologies are similar in that energy stored in the magnetic core needs to be dissipated so that the core does not saturate.
[src:boost-converter/dc-to-dc-converter] Power transmission in a flyback circuit is limited by the amount of energy that can be stored in the core, while forward circuits are usually limited by the I/V characteristics of the switches.
[src:boost-converter/dc-to-dc-converter] Although MOSFET switches can tolerate simultaneous full current and voltage (although thermal stress and electromigration can shorten the MTBF), bipolar switches generally can't so require the use of a snubber (or two).
[src:boost-converter/dc-to-dc-converter] High-current systems often use multiphase converters, also called interleaved converters.
[src:boost-converter/dc-to-dc-converter] Multiphase regulators can have better ripple and better response times than single-phase regulators.
[src:boost-converter/dc-to-dc-converter] Many laptop and desktop motherboards include interleaved buck regulators, sometimes as a voltage regulator module.
[src:boost-converter/dc-to-dc-converter] Specific to these converters is that the energy flows in both directions of the converter.
[src:boost-converter/dc-to-dc-converter] These converters are commonly used in various applications and they are connected between two levels of DC voltage, where energy is transferred from one level to another.
[src:boost-converter/dc-to-dc-converter] Multiple isolated bidirectional DC-to-DC converters are also commonly used in cases where galvanic isolation is needed.
[src:boost-converter/dc-to-dc-converter] Switched capacitor converters rely on alternately connecting capacitors to the input and output in differing topologies.
[src:boost-converter/dc-to-dc-converter] For example, a switched-capacitor reducing converter might charge two capacitors in series and then discharge them in parallel.
[src:boost-converter/dc-to-dc-converter] This would produce the same output power (less that lost to efficiency of under 100%) at, ideally, half the input voltage and twice the current.
[src:boost-converter/dc-to-dc-converter] Because they operate on discrete quantities of charge, these are also sometimes referred to as charge pump converters.
[src:boost-converter/dc-to-dc-converter] They are typically used in applications requiring relatively small currents, as at higher currents the increased efficiency and smaller size of switch-mode converters makes them a better choice.
[src:boost-converter/dc-to-dc-converter] They are also used at extremely high voltages, as magnetics would break down at such voltages.
[src:boost-converter/dc-to-dc-converter] Before the availability of power electronics devices, electromechanical converters were commercially important.
[src:boost-converter/dc-to-dc-converter] A motor–generator set consists of an electric motor and generator coupled together.
[src:boost-converter/dc-to-dc-converter] A *dynamotor* combines both functions into a single unit with coils for both the motor and the generator functions wound around a single rotor; both coils share the same outer field coils or magnets.
[src:boost-converter/dc-to-dc-converter] Typically the motor coils are driven from a commutator on one end of the shaft, when the generator coils output to another commutator on the other end of the shaft.
[src:boost-converter/dc-to-dc-converter] The entire rotor and shaft assembly is smaller in size than a pair of machines, and may not have any exposed drive shafts.
[src:boost-converter/dc-to-dc-converter] Motor–generators can convert between any combination of DC and AC voltage and phase standards.
[src:boost-converter/dc-to-dc-converter] Large motor–generator sets were widely used to convert industrial amounts of power while smaller units were used to convert battery power (6, 12 or 24 V DC) to a high DC voltage, which was required to operate vacuum tube (thermionic valve) equipment.
[src:boost-converter/dc-to-dc-converter] For lower-power requirements at voltages higher than supplied by a vehicle battery, vibrator or "buzzer" power supplies were used.
[src:boost-converter/dc-to-dc-converter] The vibrator oscillated mechanically, with contacts that switched the polarity of the battery many times per second, effectively converting DC to square wave AC, which could then be fed to a transformer of the required output voltage(s).
[src:boost-converter/dc-to-dc-converter] Electronic converters eventually replaced electromechanical converters since they had no moving parts (aside from cooling fans), and were generally smaller, lighter, and eventually cheaper than electromechanical converters of similar rating.
[src:boost-converter/dc-to-dc-converter] DC-to-DC converters are subject to different types of chaotic dynamics such as bifurcation, crisis, and intermittency.
[src:boost-converter/dc-to-dc-converter] Current and thus the magnetic field in the inductive energy storage never reaches zero.
[src:boost-converter/dc-to-dc-converter] Current and thus the magnetic field in the inductive energy storage may reach or cross zero.
[src:boost-converter/dc-to-dc-converter] at the switching frequency and its harmonics.
[src:boost-converter/dc-to-dc-converter] in continuous current mode, produce less harmonic noise than other switching converters.
[src:boost-converter/dc-to-dc-converter] Acceptable levels depend upon requirements, e.g. proximity to RF circuitry needs more suppression than simply meeting regulations.
[src:boost-converter/dc-to-dc-converter] These may include a power control IC, coil, capacitor, and resistor; decreases mounting space with a small number of components in a single integrated solution.
[src:boost-converter/dc-to-dc-converter] The input voltage may have non-negligible noise.
[src:boost-converter/dc-to-dc-converter] Additionally, if the converter loads the input with sharp load edges, the converter can emit RF noise from the supplying power lines.
[src:boost-converter/dc-to-dc-converter] This should be prevented with proper filtering in the input stage of the converter.
[src:boost-converter/dc-to-dc-converter] The output of an ideal DC-to-DC converter is a flat, constant output voltage.
[src:boost-converter/dc-to-dc-converter] However, real converters produce a DC output upon which is superimposed some level of electrical noise.
[src:boost-converter/dc-to-dc-converter] Switching converters produce switching noise at the switching frequency and its harmonics.
[src:boost-converter/dc-to-dc-converter] Some sensitive radio-frequency and analog circuits require a power supply with so little noise that it can only be provided by a linear regulator.
[src:boost-converter/dc-to-dc-converter] Some analog circuits which require a power supply with relatively low noise can tolerate some of the less-noisy switching converters, e.g. using continuous triangular waveforms rather than square waves.
